SATIRA III.

IN OBTRECTATORES ET SUPERCILIUM STOICUM.

OMNIBUS hoc vitium est cantoribus, inter amicos Ut nunquam inducant animum cantare rogati,

Sume HL— This Satire is directed against the inclination which many persons feel to put a bad construction on the actions of others, and to exaggemte the faults which they may perceive in their character or disposi- tion. This failing, which perhaps had not been very prevalent in republi- can Rome, when the citizens lived openly in each other's view, had in- mmoed under a monarchical government, in which secrecy produced mis- trust and suspicion. The satirist concludes with refuting the absurd prin- ciple of the Portico-that all faults and vices have the same degree os enormity. (Duulop’s Roman Literature, vol. iii. p. 248.)
